Mar 26 2008 	Havana - south east london style	I want to avoid being cliched, but there's no other way of saying this...this hotel really is a fantatsic undiscovered little gem, - if only I could afford to live here permanently, i'd rent an entire suite of rooms!. I'm a great fan of things Cubana/o/Mexicano, and so this hotel really ticked all my boxes. Last year, I had the misfortune of staying in in a popular minimalist but overpriced and over-rated hotel in London...and absolutely hated it. This hotel however, grabbed me by the throat from the minute I saw its fantastically colourful website - Strangely enough, I'm a south Londoner and live only a couple miles away from the hotel, so ordinarily would have had no cause to be staying here...but for reasons too complicated to go into here, I found myself in need of a place to stay for a couple of nights. Having trawled the internet for available hotels in the area - and having spent the previous couple of nights in what could only be described as a Reggie Perrin/Maunela style firetrap just a few blocks along, I could hardly believe my luck when I discovered that not only was this fantastic place just minutes away, but that a room was available and ready and waiting for me...I loved the fact that so much attention had been given to every detail of the Mexican/Cuban decor - from the minute you walk into the reception, it feels as though you've stepped off an aeroplane in Havana [minus the insufferably long airport queue and equally insufferable sultry heat ]. The owners/staff were really helpful, friendly, cool, but always professional - I was shown into the 'red room' a small but perfectly gorgeous en-suite small terracotta bedroom with a huge and incredibly comfortable iron four poster bed, beautiful tile work , a selection of books, television, complimentary Green and Black organic chocolate bar, and the most gorgeous Mexican/Moorish bathroom cum shower-room. again with complimentary high quality soap, shampoos etc, fluffy white towels...absolute bliss...I could easily have spent my entire two days just luxuriating in this room, were it not for the honesty bar and the sumptuous breakfasts... The only thing lacking was a restaurant, but then there's a great choice of ethnic restaurants right on the door-step. Some people might turn their noses up at the thought of staying in a hotel in Camberwell, but there's such an incredible vibrancy to the area that its hard not to be captivated by the sheer colour and buzz of Camberwell itself...which after all, is only 20 minutes away from Central London [and minutes away also from Great little East Street market!] , the Oval Crciket ground, and a short bus-ride away from local attractions such as Brixton market, the Fridge or the Brixton Academy. Camberwell is actually quite an interesting place in all sorts of ways, and the local council really has to find ways of better exploiting its many attractions...its incredibly multi-cultural, and comfortably so; there are some lovely little hidden gardens and parks, pretty close to Brockwell Park's fabulous open air lido, some wonderful Victorian architecture, grocery stores selling foodstuffs from just about every corner of the world, and yes, while it may feel as though ambulance sirens, form an almost constant audio backdrop, it's not surprising given that its just around the corner from King's College, one of London's busiest teaching/university hospitals - the noise and general bustle just all adds to the overall sense of pervasive excitement ..yes, the nearest tube station [Oval] is about 20 minutes walk away, but Camberwell is incredibly well-served by regular bus services which will get you to just about anywhere you want to get to in London - and places beyond!What made this hotel stay really special for me was that I was actually staying there just a few days before my first ever visit to Mexico, so it really got me into the Mexican spirit ...And though, as I said, I live just a couple of miles away from here, I've pledged to stay here at leasts twice a year as a refuge from my own hectic and noisy over-crowded Forest Hill home...	
