Sep 3 2007 	Church Street Hotel: an unexpected oasis in South London	My daughter recommended the Church Street Hotel as 'a place you'd like, mum' on the occasion of her wedding in nearby Dulwich. Upon checking out the beautifully designed website, I was pretty sure she was right.We had a slightly complicated set of arrangements involving husbands, boyfriends, sisters and friends arriving and departing at different times, all of which were dealt with with efficiency and charm by the friendly proprietors. The hotel itself is delightfully quirky if a little unexpected in Camberwell; recently refurbished by Jose Raido, each room is beautifully and individually decorated in strong, deep colours with a Spanish theme, reflecting the origins of the Raido brothers. An honesty bar (for drinks) and complimentary bars of Green and Black's organic chocolate and aged chilli sauce in the rooms made us feel at home, while the spacious and luxurious bathroom, with its large and luxurious white towels, augmented by Korres natural shampoos, soaps and conditioners, made us feel we were on holiday.Breakfast is an informal and relaxed affair, with organic cereals and yoghourt, freshly-baked pastries, boiled eggs and the best coffee I've had for some time. All the staff were incredibly friendly and helpul and even bothered to get to know our names - and all that in spite of having to cope with two wedding parties at breakfast time on Saturday!Wi-fi is complimentary throughout the hotel enabled me to do some work while good flat screen televisions offered alternative entertainment for those so inclined. I preferred to explore Camberwell and dip into the interesting selection of books left on my bedside table; a good range of DVDs was also available to borrow.The nearest tube station is 10-15 minutes' walk but buses are just a few minutes' walk away and provide a pleasant 20 minute trip to central London.The only downside was the noise outside the window, which went on until the early hours of the morning - we were fortunate in having a room at the back and, since I had been warned, I had packed a pair of ear plugs - it is worth taking this precaution to avoid marring what was otherwise a completely delightful experience and, in my book, extremely good value for money.I certainly hope to go back and would recommended it unhesitatingly; I'm looking forward to trying the restaurant (work in progress) next time!	
